What's the difference between calling task.run() and new Thread(task).start()? Try both and observe what happens. Which one creates actual concurrency?
    task.run() is a normal method call. It executes the logic on the current thread and is synchronous, meaning that the program waits for it to finish
    before moving to the next line.
    new Thread(task).start() tells the JVM to allocate a new entry in the OS's thread scheduler. It creates actual concurrency since it runs the run()
    method on a completely separate execution path.
Why do the threads finish in different orders each time you run option 2? What does this tell you about concurrent execution?
    They finish in different orders because of the Thread Scheduler.
    It shows that concurrent execution is non-deterministic. You can't rely on the timing or order of execution unless you use explicit synchronization.
What would happen if you didn't call join() before accessing the results? Try removing the join() calls - what goes wrong?
    The Results would print out as incomplete data.
How does thread execution interleave? Notice how the console output from different threads mixes together. Is this random?
    The OS scheduler rapidly switches the CPU between active threads. This creates the illusion of simultaneous progress. Technically, it is random to
    humans, but it is actually determined by the scheduler's algorithm (which factors in priority and CPU load).
Why do we need the Thread.sleep() calls in the calculations? What happens if you remove them? Does it affect correctness or just visibility?
    It simulates "busy work" or computational load. Without it, modern CPUs would finish the math so fast that you wouldn't be able to observe the 
    threads running at the same time.
    If you remove it, the threads will likely finish one after the other almost instantly.
    It affects just visibility.
What happens to the calc object when you create the Runnable? How does the thread access the same CalculatorBase instance?
    The Runnable captures a reference to the CalculatorBase object. Threads in Java share the same memory space. Since you pass the same reference to
    the CalculatorBase object into the thread, both the worker thread and the main thread are looking at the exact same spot in memory. This allows the
    worker thread to store the answer in calc.result and the main thread to read it after the join() call completes.
Can you use a lambda expression instead of an anonymous class? Which style is more concise? Which is clearer?
    You can use a lambda expression.
    Lambda expressions are more concise because they remove the "boilerplate" code.
    Lambdas are usually considered clearer for simpler tasks since they focus strictly on the logic being performed instead of the syntax of the interface.
